🔐 The Hackbox — In Depth
The Visitor Experience
A visitor walks up to a locked wooden or plastic box. A screen (or printed card) tells them: "This box contains a prize / secret message / trophy. Can you hack your way in?"
They work through 3 stages in sequence. Each stage is a short puzzle. Solving it correctly triggers a satisfying LED flash and unlocks the next stage. Completing all three releases a physical latch (controlled by the Pi via a relay), and the box clicks open. Their completion time is logged on a leaderboard.
It can be played solo or as a pair — ideal for a festival setting.

The Three Puzzle Stages
Stage 1 — Spot the Phishing Email

A tablet or small screen shows two side-by-side emails. One is legitimate, one is a phishing attempt (dodgy sender address, fake urgency, suspicious link). The visitor presses a Red or Green button on the breadboard to choose. Get it right → green LED pulse, move on. Get it wrong → red flash, try again (with a time penalty).
Stage 2 — Caesar Cipher Decoder

A short encrypted message is displayed (e.g. KHOOR ZRUOG = HELLO WORLD with a shift of 3). A rotary encoder or number buttons let the visitor try different shift values. When they land on the correct plaintext, they confirm with a button press. This stage teaches the most basic form of encryption in a hands-on way.
Stage 3 — Password Strength Puzzle

Four passwords are shown on screen. The visitor must rank them from weakest to strongest using numbered buttons. The "correct" order is based on real password security rules (length, symbols, no dictionary words). This is the most thought-provoking stage and sparks genuine conversation.

