Software Architecture 

┌─────────────────────────────┐
│        Raspberry Pi         │
│                             │
│  game_controller.py         │  ← main loop, tracks stage + timer
│  puzzles/                   │
│    phishing.py              │  ← Stage 1 logic
│    caesar.py                │  ← Stage 2 logic
│    password.py              │  ← Stage 3 logic
│  hardware/                  │
│    gpio_handler.py          │  ← button input, LED output
│    relay.py                 │  ← lock control
│  leaderboard/               │
│    submit_score.py          │  ← sends time to server via HTTP
└─────────────────────────────┘
          │
          ▼ HTTP POST
┌─────────────────────────────┐
│     Server (Flask / Pi)     │
│  leaderboard_api.py         │  ← receives and stores scores
│  leaderboard.html           │  ← live display for nearby screen
└─────────────────────────────┘

The main loop is straightforward: track which stage the player is on, listen for GPIO button presses, validate the answer, give feedback via LEDs, and advance or penalise accordingly. On completion, fire the relay and POST the time to the server.

How Data Flows

Visitor starts → Pi records a start timestamp
Each correct answer → Pi logs the stage completion time
Box opens → Pi calculates total time, optionally adds a name/initials via buttons or touchscreen
Score is POSTed to a Flask server running on a second Pi or laptop on the local network
The leaderboard page auto-refreshes every few seconds and displays on a second screen nearby
All scores are written to a SQLite database or CSV — you have a full dataset of attempts at the end of the day

